{{about|the Greek [[Daemon (classical mythology)|daemon]]|other uses of this name|Agathodaemon (disambiguation)}} [[Image:Antinoos-Agathodaimon Antikensammlung Berlin Sk361.jpg|thumb|upright|A Roman marble sculpture of Agathodaemon restored with an unrelated head, as "[[Antinous]] Agathodaemon", purchased in Rome ca. 1760, ([[Staatliche Museen]], Berlin)<ref>The torso of an [[Apollo]] was found in the [[Tiber]] at Rome and was restored as an [[Antinous]] with a head found separately; it was purchased through [[Giovanni Ludovico Bianconi]], about 1760; formerly exhibited in the [[Neues Palais]], Potsdam ([http://arachne.uni-koeln.de/dump/objekt/objekt_2181.html Arachne Projekt]{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}); noted in [[Karl Otfried Müller]], ''Nouveau manuel complet d'archéologie ou traité sur les antiquités grecques...'' (1841:vol. I:298) and in Bouillon II:51.</ref>]]
An '''agathodaemon''' ({{lang-grc-gre|ἀγαθοδαίμων}}, ''agathodaímōn'') or '''agathos daemon''' ({{lang-grc-gre|{{linktext|ἀγαθός}} {{linktext|δαίμων}}}}, ''agathós daímōn'', {{abbr|lit.|Literally}}&nbsp;"noble spirit") was a [[spiritual being|spirit]] (''[[daemon (mythology)|daemon]]'') of the [[vineyard]]s and [[cereal|grain]]fields in [[ancient Greek religion]]. They were personal companion spirits,<ref>Hor. Ep. ll, 2, 187.</ref><ref>Tibull. IV, 8</ref> comparable to the Roman ''[[Genius (mythology)|genii]]'', who ensured good [[luck]], [[health]], and [[wisdom]].
==During the classical period== Though little noted in [[Greek mythology]] ([[Pausanias (geographer)|Pausanias]] conjectured that the name was merely an epithet of [[Zeus]]),<ref>[[Pausanias (geographer)|Pausanias]], ''Description of Greece'', viii. 36. § 3</ref> he was prominent in Greek folk religion;<ref>[[Martin P. Nilsson]], ''Greek Folk Religion''. (Columbia University Press), 1981:33, 70, 73.</ref> it was customary to [[Libation|drink or pour out a few drops]] of unmixed [[wine]] to honor him in every [[symposium]] or formal [[banquet]]. In [[Aristophanes]]' ''[[Peace (play)|Peace]]'', when War has trapped Peace (Εἰρήνη ''[[Eirene (Greek goddess)|Eirene]]'') in a deep pit, Hermes comes to give aid: "Now, oh Greeks! is the moment when, freed of quarrels and fighting, we should rescue sweet ''Eirene'' and draw her out of this pit... This is the moment to drain a cup in honor of the ''Agathos Daimon''." A temple dedicated to him was situated on the road from [[Megalopolis, Greece|Megalopolis]] to [[Mainalo|Maenalus]] in [[Arcadia]].<ref name="DGRBM">{{Citation | last = Schmitz | first = Leonhard | author-link = | contribution = Agathodaemon | editor-last = Smith | editor-first = William | title = [[Dictionary of Greek and Roman Biography and Mythology]] | volume = 1 | pages = 65 | publisher = | place = Boston | year = 1867 | contribution-url = http://www.ancientlibrary.com/smith-bio/0074.html }}</ref>
''Agathos Daimon'' was the spouse or companion of ''[[Tyche]] Agathe'' ({{lang|grc|Τύχη Ἀγαθή}}, "Good Fortune"; {{lang-la|Agatha}}). "Tyche we know at [[Livadeia|Lebadeia]] as the wife of the Agathos Daimon, the Good or Rich Spirit".{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=371}}{{sfn|Harrison|1922|pp=355–ff, 543}} His [[Numen|numinous presence]] could be represented in art as a [[Serpent (symbolism)|serpent]] or more concretely as a young man bearing a [[cornucopia]] and a bowl in one hand, and a [[Poppy (flower)|poppy]] and an ear of grain in the other.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=371}} The agathodaemon was later adapted into a general [[Daemon (mythology)|daemon]] of ''[[fortuna]]'', particularly of the continued abundance of a family's good [[food]] and [[drink]].{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}
==During late antiquity== In the [[syncretism|syncretic atmosphere]] of [[Late Antiquity]], agathodaemons could be bound up with Egyptian bringers of security and good fortune: a gem carved with magic emblems bears the images of [[Serapis]] with crocodile, sun-lion and [[Osiris]] mummy surrounded by the lion-headed snake Cnum–Agathodaemon–[[Aion (deity)|Aion]], with [[Harpocrates]] on the reverse.<ref>Illustrated in W. Fauth, ''Helios Megistos: zur synkretistischen Theologie der Spätantike'' (Leiden: Brill) 1995:85.</ref>
