[[Capital punishment]] is a legal penalty in the [[East Africa]]n nation of [[Somalia]]. In 2011 three soldiers were executed for [[murder]] by the [[Transitional Federal Government]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deathpenaltyworldwide.org/country-search-post.cfm?country=somalia|title=The Death Penalty in Somalia|work=[[Cornell Law School]]|publisher=Death Penalty Worldwide|accessdate=2 January 2018}}</ref> The activist [[Non-governmental organization|NGO]] [[Human Rights Watch]] noted in 2014 that [[summary execution]]s were on the rise in the nation.<ref>{{cite news|last=Laetitia|first=Baeder|title=Summary executions in Somalia|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2014/08/25/summary-executions-somalia|work=[[Al Jazeera]]|publisher=[[Human Rights Watch]]|date=25 August 2014|accessdate=2 January 2018}}</ref> At least 14 executions were carried out in 2016,<ref>{{cite web|title=Death sentences and executions in 2016|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/documents/act50/5740/2017/en/|publisher=[[Amnesty International]]|date=11 April 2017|accessdate=2 January 2018}}</ref> and the rate of executions rose in 2017, which human rights groups mainly attributed to [[military court]]s and the militant [[Jihadism|jihadist]] group [[Al-Shabaab (militant group)|Al-Shabaab]]. The [[European Union]] requested that Somalia enact a [[Moratorium (law)|moratorium]] on the death penalty as a result.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hassan|first1=Mohamed Olad|title=Executions Increase in Somalia|url=https://www.voanews.com/a/executions-increase-in-somalia/3851581.html|accessdate=2 January 2018|publisher=[[Voice of America]]|date=15 May 2017}}</ref>
