{{Infobox film | name = Doctors of the Dark Side | image = Doctors of the Dark Side Logo.png | image_size = | alt = | caption = | director = Martha Davis | producer = Martha Davis | writer = [[Mark Jonathan Harris]] | narrator = Mercedes Ruehl | starring = Diane Davis, Gian-Murray Gianino, Lee Aaron Rosen, Joe Tippett, Rafael Wurzel | music = Maxim Moston | cinematography = Lisa Rinzler | editing = M. Trevino | studio = | distributor = Shelter Island | released = 2011 | runtime = 73 minutes | country = US | language = English | budget = | gross = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }} '''''Doctors of the Dark Side''''' is a [[documentary]] about the role of [[physician]]s and [[psychologist]]s in the [[torture of prisoners]]. The movie tells the story of four detainees, and how healthcare professionals working for the [[United States Army]] and the [[Central Intelligence Agency]] implemented [[enhanced interrogation techniques]], and covered up signs of torture at the [[Guantanamo Bay Detention Camp]] and [[Baghdad Central Prison|Abu Ghraib Prison]].<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2006722/?ref_=ttpl_pl_tt "Doctors of the Dark Side"] in ''[[Internet Movie Database]]'' (4 August 2011). Retrieved 26 October 2013.</ref><ref>Finnegan, Colin. [http://www.gulawweekly.org/features/2011/10/31/doctors-of-the-dark-side-provokes-professional-responsibilit.html "Doctors of the Dark Side provokes professional responsibility debate"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029200246/http://www.gulawweekly.org/features/2011/10/31/doctors-of-the-dark-side-provokes-professional-responsibilit.html |date=October 29, 2013 }} in ''[[Georgetown Law Weekly]]'' (31 October 2011). Retrieved 26 October 2013.</ref> Interviews with medical, legal and intelligence experts and evidence from [[declassification|declassified]] government memos document how the torture of detainees could not continue without the assistance of doctors.
