The '''Eastern Cooperative Oncology Group''' ('''ECOG''') began in 1955 as one of the first [[National Cancer Institute|publicly funded]] cooperative groups to perform multi-center [[clinical trials]] for cancer research.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.medpagetoday.com/PublicHealthPolicy/ClinicalTrials/8878 | title=NCI-Sponsored Cancer Trials Offer Decent Clinical Return on Investment | work=MedPage Today | date=March 24, 2008 | accessdate=September 17, 2016 | author=Crystal Phend}}</ref> A cooperative group in [[oncology]] constitutes a large network of private and public medical institutions developing   [[Medical guideline|protocols]] for cancer treatments. Institutional members include universities, medical centers, governments, and other cooperative groups. Research results are often provided through scientific publications, but the group also works closely with the [[pharmaceutical]] industry to test potential cancer drugs.

[[Image:ECOG logo.gif|thumb|right|400px|Eastern Cooperative Oncology Group]]
According to ECOG's website, there are "more than 90 active clinical trials in all types of adult malignancies. Annual accrual is 6,000 patients, with more than 20,000 patients in follow-up."<ref name="Introduction to ECOG">{{cite web|url=http://ecog.dfci.harvard.edu/general/intro.html|title=Introduction to ECOG|date=June 6, 2006|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130520202454/http://ecog.dfci.harvard.edu/general/intro.html|archivedate=May 20, 2013|deadurl=y}}</ref>

ECOG's coordinating center is based in [[Boston, Massachusetts]] while its Group Chair's office is located in [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]].

