{{Infobox person | name = Leopold William Brandenburg | image = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | nationality = American | other_names = | occupation = | years_active = | known_for = | notable_works = }} '''Leopold William Brandenburg''' (born 1886) was a 20th century American [[Physician|doctor]] and [[criminal]]. He became notorious after surgically changing the fingerprints and "facial contour" of criminal Ronald Philipps, a.k.a. "Roscoe Pitts," in 1941, for which he was sentenced to three years in prison, although the sentence was later overturned.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1943/08/25/83937366.html?pageNumber=21|title=Dr. Brandenburg is Freed|date=25 August 1943|publisher=The New York Times|accessdate=16 April 2016}}</ref> Pitts had attempted to rob a grocery store using explosives in [[Wilkesboro, North Carolina]].
Brandenburg was later sentenced to five years in prison for illicitly prescribing [[morphine]], a narcotic, to patients.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1946/10/18/94066180.html?pageNumber=19|title=Physician Found Guilty|date=18 October 1946|publisher=The New York Times|accessdate=16 April 2016}}</ref>
