[[Image:Periodontium.svg|thumb|right|The [[gingival sulcus]] ''(G)'' is bounded by the [[Tooth enamel|enamel]] ''(A)'' of the [[crown (tooth)|crown]] of the [[tooth]] and the '''sulcular epithelium'''. The sulcular epithelium is that epithelium which exists on the sulcular side of the free gingival margin ''(F)''. The oral epithelium ''(E)'' exists on the other side of the free gingival margin.]] The '''sulcular epithelium''' is that [[epithelium]] which lines the [[gingival sulcus]].<ref name="Carranza's Clinical Periodontology 2002, page 23">Carranza's Clinical Periodontology, W.B. Saunders, 2002, page 23.</ref> It is [[Commonly used terms of relationship and comparison in dentistry|apically]] bounded by the [[junctional epithelium]] and meets the epithelium of the [[oral cavity]] at the height of the [[free gingival margin]]. The sulcular epithelium is [[keratinized|nonkeratinized]].<ref name="Carranza's Clinical Periodontology 2002, page 23"/>
